And Boothroyd was pleased with the start his Young Lions, who also featured two players from League Two Exeter City, made to the tournament.

He told The FA.com: ‘We’re delighted to start off with a victory against a very strong German team.

'When we looked at their squad we could see they had a lot of players born in 1994, so many were a year older than ours.

'They had a number of players that had won the U19 European Championship too – so to start off with a win against that side is very pleasing.

'It was a tight game. We’ve hit the post, they’ve hit the post and we’ve both a number of good chance too.

'But in the end it was down to an own-goal caused by some really good attacking play which sealed it.’

